A fifth-generation Subaru Sambar. Specifically, a Sambar Try RJ Extra S. Also, three dogs.
-
The fifth-gen Sambar was sold from 1990 through 1999. Without getting too into the weeds, this seems to be an early 90s example. The 'Try' designation seems to refer to the van bodystyle of the Sambar, and Try models were offered in a high-roof passenger version, seen here. If you have any knowledge of the 'RJ' suffix, and/or 'Extra S' designation, please share.
---
#Subaru #Sambar #JDM #KeiCar #KeiVan

A 2021 or 2022 Chevrolet Colorado ZR2 AEV Bison extended cab fitted with the 2.8-liter ‘Duramax’ turbodiesel engine. The holy-grail of second-gen Colorados. Someone here paid almost $55,000 for a truck configured for a very specific use case. Opting for the extended cab over the roomier crew cab means trading off passenger room for bed space. Forgoing the mass-market V6 for the less common 4-cylinder turbodiesel means sacrificing $4,000 and the ability to keep up on the highway in exchange for better fuel economy, range, and low-end torque. Checking the box for the AEV Bison package means forking over $6,000 in exchange for what amounts to better rock protection. All in the name of maximizing capability, functionality, and performance in rough, remote places. There isn’t a midsize truck that gets me more excited. Not many people could justify buying a Colorado configured this way though, and thus, very few would’ve been built in this configuration. As a result of that though, this truck should have better resale value than any other Colorado; maybe even any other midsize truck. I said a while back that a Colorado in this spec would be the most obscure and interesting midsize pickup ever sold in the United States. But I wasn’t holding my breath when it came to actually encountering one in real life (to this day, I’ve probably seen fewer than 10 Bisons running around in total). Needless to say, I got excited when I realized this one checked all the boxes.
-
#Chevrolet #Colorado #ZR2 #AEV #Bison #AEVBison #Duramax

An International Harvester Scout 800, built from 1965 to 1968. The Scout 800 shared this general body style with the Scout 80 that preceded it, and the Scout 800A and 800B, both of which followed. I'm concluding this is a Scout 800 based on the rectangular "International" wordmark in the grille. This bit shrinks and moves to the driver's-side bottom corner of the grille on the 800A. The Scout II, which replaced the 80/800 series, went on sale in April of 1971 and was sold through 1980.
-
Looking through these photos and that kind of looks like some sort of low-production Lamborghini Aventador model parked behind the Scout there. I assure you, it was not.
-
#Scout #IHScout #Scout800 #InternationalHarvester #Scout80 #ScoutII

A 4WD fourth-generation Toyota HiAce Ambulance. The fourth-gen HiAce was sold from the 1990 through 2004 model years. This would make for a pretty good camping rig - there's even already a bed inside. But you'd have to be willing to ignore A LOT.
-
I used to automatically photograph every JDM vehicle I'd see, but these days, given that the good JDM stuff has now been flowing into the US since around 2014, I pass up a lot.
---
#JDM #Toyota #HiAce #Ambulance #Overland #4x4van

Spent some time in Sedona a few weeks ago. If you've been, or maybe even if you haven't, you probably know about the pink Jeep tours. In total I counted four different tour companies, which I identify here by the types of vehicles they used - 1) Pink Jeep Wranglers (TJs and JK Unlimiteds), 2) Red Jeep Gladiators, 3) Hummers, and 4) Green/Silver Jeep Gladiators, also pictured here. These Gladiators I was particularly intrigued by - from the looks of it, they achieved the 'group safari' configuration by removing the panel of sheet metal from the back of the cabs and off of the front of the beds, making for one big combined area. This is either structural suicide or a criminally underutilized modification for the overlanding community. I'm assuming the former - it looked like supplemental bracing had maybe been added to these. I also noticed the window frames had been lopped off of the back doors. Seems like factory half doors would've been easier.
---
#Sedona #PinkJeeps #JeepTours #RedRocks #JeepWrangler #JeepGladiator

An eighth-generation Suzuki Carry. The eighth-gen Carry was primarily built from the 1985 through 1991 model years, though production in Vietnam apparently continues to this day. Based on the front of this one, it appears to be a facelifted 1990 or 1991 model.
-
I came upon this thing off of a random exit on US 40 just west of Holbrook, Arizona. Route 66 country - I don’t think I’ve ever driven through a more desolate portion of the US. The era when Route 66 served as an actual transportation route is obviously long gone, but I got the impression that its second act as a tourist attraction is coming to an end as well. Driving through Holbrook, Winslow, and Petrified Forest National Park felt like showing up to a party just to watch the last people leave. Those who remember Route 66 as a beacon of 20th-century Americana are aging out, and I imagine the generations that follow will be less than amused by the corporate truck stops and chain restaurants that have taken over. 21st Century America baby.
—
#Suzuki #KeiTruck #MiniTruck #SuzukiCarry #Route66

An oddly-modified Suzuki Samurai. I was in Sedona for a week, and for that entire time, this Samurai sat outside the post office, not moving once. It's probably still there. On one hand, it seems to be pretty sensibly built, on the other, it was packed with belongings and showing some signs of neglect. Not sure what's going on with that body kit either. Seeing a rare vehicle with an expensive modification like that always piques my interest.
---
#Suzuki #Samurai #ToyZukiVergnügen

A 1991 GMC Syclone. I think this is the third Syclone I've posted, which is just over 0.1% of the 2,998 made in total, all but three of which came for the 1991 model year.
-
Oddly, I've not posted any of the Syclone's GMC Jimmy-based sibling, the Typhoon, despite 4,697 being built over the 1992 and 1993 model years. Given those production numbers, you should see three Typhoons for every two Syclones, meaning I should've noticed at least four Typhoons in this timeframe. In reality, I can vaguely recall catching a glimpse of what might've been one in an intersection in downtown SLC a few years ago, but even then, we're still three short.
---

A Mercedes-Benz 1017 with a modified tow-behind Lance camper mounted to the rear. Any time I post one of these - the last time was October 2018 - I feel the need to reiterate that the 1017 is not a Unimog, but rather the military version of Mercedes-Benz' 'NG' line of commercial trucks sold from 1973 through 1988. A version of the NG was sold in the US, but the 1017 wasn't, which tells us that this one likely originated in Europe, prior to its California registration. Both 2WD and 4WD versions of the 1017 were offered with 4WD versions known as the 1017A. None of the badging on the cab of this one explicitly says it's a 1017A, but is that a driveshaft running to the front wheels?
---
#Mercedes #MercedesBenz #MercedesNG #Mercedes1017 #Mercedes1017A #Unimog #Gelandewagen #AdventureVehicle

​​A Mitsubishi Delica L300. There tends to be a lot to digest with these, kind of like how if humans encountered aliens, we wouldn’t be able to even process what we were looking at because no frame of reference would theoretically exist between the two worlds unless the human and alien worlds had in fact split off from one another at some point in the distant past, but recently enough that some basic connections still exist between the two worlds. That’s basically an American looking at a Delica. You know it’s a vehicle, you see the wheels, you probably know what emblem is on the front, but beyond that everything is mush. So here, I’ll try to parse this one out:
- Given the front-end design, this one would be a 1991-1993 model, as opposed to an earlier 86-90.
- It had to have been privately imported into the US, and only after it was 25 years old, based on its build date. So the earliest this one could’ve been built was say mid-late 1990, meaning the earliest it could’ve been legally registered in the US is mid-late 2015.
- It's the shorter and more common of two available wheelbases.
- All passenger L300s carried ‘Star Wagon’ branding - nothing too special there.
- These came with either a very basic gas or very basic diesel engine. The ‘Turbo D’ on the liftgate of this one tells us it's a diesel. 86 hp, 148 lb-ft. Good luck in any of the canyons.
- It's a 4WD model - transfer case lever confirms it. Not much point in owning one that isn't.
- It's got the optional high roof, which is probably what you want, but not the special Crystal Lite skylight roof, which you probably don’t want anyway.
- It’s hard to say what trim level it is.
- I can't tell if the sticker on the side is a reproduction.
–
For a great high-level rundown on the Delica as it relates to the US, check out @andy_lilienthal’s recent “The Ultimate Mitsubishi Delica Van Guide” article on @TheGearJunkie. For a more granular look at all the L300’s different trim levels, including the Chamonix, Jasper, and Active World, look up my article, “The Mitsubishi Delica Had The Best Trim Levels” on Autotrader from a while back.
—
#Mitsubishi #Delica #L300 #MitsubishiDelica #DelicaL300 #VanLife

A Volkswagen Dasher Station Wagon. Here in North America, the first-generation Passat was marketed as the 'Dasher', and sold in three- and five-door hatchback body styles, in addition to the wagon you see here. The first-gen or 'B1' Passat was built from 1973 through 1981, with North American sales starting in 1974. The 'Diesel' badge on the back of this one tells us it's, at the oldest, a 1979 model.
-
The B1 Passat was also sold as the Audi 80 - I hadn't realized Volkswagen and Audi had ever engaged in that degree of badge engineering.
-
For someone who started their career in product planning at Volkswagen Group of America, my knowledge of these early VW models is pretty weak. On that note though, the company's often-chaotic product and branding decisions are also, in large part, what make it so interesting.
---
#Volkswagen #VW #Dasher #Passat #VolkswagenDasher #B1Passat

A 1992 Daihatsu Charade. Daihatsu lasted just over four years in the United States, from 1988 to early 1992, and in that time offered a total of three models; the 3-door Charade seen here, a Charade sedan, and the Rocky, a convertible Suzuki Sidekick-sized SUV. I've seen and posted a handful of Rockys; given the inherent fun-factor of a convertible 4x4, they seem to be the Daihatsu that people are most interested in keeping on the road. This is an example of how cars with enthusiast appeal maintain their values better than commodity vehicles like the Charade. While the Charade was sold in far greater numbers than the Rocky, its status as little more than a transportation appliance means that most have just been junked over the past 30 years, hence the reason they aren't as prevalent today. As with everything, there's some nuance to this, but in essence, a commodity vehicle will be viewed as value-less long before an enthusiast car, let alone an enthusiast car that also offers good utility. Another example (and Toyota owns Daihatsu these days, so I'm not veering too far off course here) - my 08 Land Cruiser will hold its value better than a fifth-gen 4Runner, which will hold its value better than a RAV4, which will hold its value better than a Camry. I'll stop short of trying to come up with a mathematical equation for all of this.
-
This is (I think) the third 3-door Charade I've posted, the last was a much nicer example I saw back in January 2020. The Charade sedan has proven to be the most elusive of the US-market Daihatsu trio - I've yet to see one since I started this back in 2016.
---
#Daihatsu #DaihatsuCharade #DaihatsuRocky
